 Education; Mrs.\nRosa Slade Gragg, chairman of\nthe Detroit Welfare Commission;\nMrs. Julia West Hamilton, presi\ndent of the Phyllis Wheatley\nYWCA here; Mrs. Marjorie Stew\nart Joyner, president of the Na\ntional Beauty Culturlst League of\nAmerica; Miss Frieda Miller, chief\nof the Women's Bureau, Labor\nDepartment: Miss Muriel Rahn,\nconcert and opera singer, and\nRepresentative Woodhouse, Dem\nocrat, of Connecticut.\nPour of the awards were re\nceived by proxy in the absence of\nthe recipients. They were accept\ned for Dr. Ethel Alpenfels, an\nthropologist; Dr. Charlotte Hawk\ning Brown, founder and president\nof the Palmer Memorial Insti\ntute. Sedalia, N. C.; Dr. Martha\nM. Eliot, assistant director gen\neral of the World Health Organ\nization, and Cornelia Otis Skin\nner, the actress.\nWAAWillSeliTract\nNear Newport News\n\u2022y the Associated Press\nNEWPORT NEWS. Va\u201e June\n20.\u2014The War Assets Administra\ntion has advertised for sale 323\nacres of surplus wartime housing\ndevelopment land at Copeland\nPark near Newport News.\nw/Mfmemm\nFurs Out of Season\nShould Bo Freozin' if\nThe reason furs out of season\nshould be freesln' ts purely sclent!-\nflc! The Rainbow Dyelns Clean- HQ\nIns Co. can store your precious furs M\nsafely during the summer months HR\nIn chemical storage which\nthe Bureau of Standards recom- QB\nmends In preference to cold stor- flH\nage to preserve the luxury of Mb\nthe skins and protect It from 9BR\nmoths. Call now for a quick\ncuaning ||1\nATIantic 6400\nMM\nH\nPrice\nHearth Co.\n3289 M St. N.W.\nMISS AVIATION-** Miss\nDaphne Jeanette Lockamy,\n20-year-old telephone operator\nof 816 Fiftieth avenue, Capitol\nHeights, Md., has been chosen\nto represent the District in\nTrans World Airline\u2019s national\nsearch for a queen. The occa\nsion will be July 8, the 20th\nanniversary of TWA\u2019s first\ntranscontinental flight.\nVA to Pay 2.8 Billion\nInsurance Dividend;\n16 Million to Benefit\nVeterans\u2019 Administrator Carl R.\nGray, Jr., announced today that\nhe had authorized the payment\nof $2,800,000,000 in dividends on\nNational Service Life Insurance\npolicies. He added that 16,000,000\nveterans of World War n will be\neligible to collect on 20,000,000\npolicies, explaining that some vet\nerans had two or more policies.\nAlthough exact amounts to be\npaid on each policy have not been\ndetermined, since the audit still is\ngoing on, it is planned now to be\ngin the payments next January\nwith the expectation that it will be\ncompleted during the first six\nmonths of the year.\nHowever, veterans are urged not\nto write to the bureau. Machinery\nnow is being set up to handle ap\nplications and they are expected\nto be available in August at every\npost office, veterans service organ\nization and VA office in the coun\nty.\nIt will consist of a three-fold\ncard on which the veteran is to\nwrite his full name, service num\nber, insurance policy numbers and\nhis address. He is to retain one\nthird of the card which contains\nthe instructions. The other parts\nare to be sent to VA where the\napplication part of the card is to\nbe separated, and the other sent\nback to the veteran to acknowl\nedge receipt. Any letter writing.\nMr. Gray explained, will only\ncomplicate and delay the pay\nments.\nMr. Gray explained every vet\neran who took out insurance and\nkept it in force for three months\nor more will be eligible for a di\nvidend. In cases where the policy\nholders have died, the benefici\nary, if the insurance was in force,\nor to those shown to be entitled in\ncase the insurance had lapsed,\nwill receive payment.\nThere currently are 7,215,000\npolicies In force, with a face value\nOf $41,522,000,000. '\u25a0v\nThe cut-off date for the pay\nment of the dividend, he said, is\nthe anniversary date of the pol\nicy during 1948. The special di\nvidend will not be paid on policies\nissued after January 1. 1948,\nthough such policyHolders may\nparticipate in some later dividend.\nA premature announcement of\nthe action was put out by VA\nyesterday, but recalled because\nMr. Gray had not yet signed the\norder. He signed it this morn\ning. _\nDon Hutchinson Dead\nSAN FRANCISCO. June 19 (/P).\n\u2014Don W. Hutchinson, widely\nknown sports writer and pub\nlicist, died early today at Letter\nman General Hospital here. He\nwas *64 years old._\nNew Zealand hopes to develop\na large seed export trade to the\nUnited 8tates.\n1\nAFl Sees 5,000,000\nJobless by July but\nNo Serious Recession\nThe American Federation of\nLabor believes \u201ca serious business\nrecession is almost Impossible.\u201d\nwhile admitting the Nation's un\nemployed may reach a total of 5\n000.000 by July.\nThe appraisal is made in \u201cLa\nbor's Monthly Survey.'' made pub\nlic today.\nThe sanguine view is contrary\nto that of the Public Affairs In\nstitute. which warned, in a re\nport made public over the week\nend. that \u201cnothing in sight indi\ncates a halt in unemployment\ntrends.\u201d\nMeanwhile. Senator O'Mahoney.\nDemocrat, of Wyoming said opin\nions generally are confused con\ncerning the extent and course of\nunemployment\nThe Senate-House Economic\nCommittee, which he heads, will\nstart inquiries next month into\nunemployment and the invest\nment situation.\nIn its survey, the AFL stated it\nis necessary that wages move\n\"steadily upward\" this year to\nboost consumer buying power.\nIt urged, however, that unions\nco-operate with management to\n\u201cprevent waste, save expense, cut\ncosts, improve production.\"\nCompany earning power should\nbe considered carefully in deter\nmining future changes in wage\nlevels, and increases should be\nbased on \u201cpast or future increases\nin productivity.\u201d the report added.\nConcerning economic prospects\nthe AFL said current price reduc\ntions are a \"healthy development.\"\nIt Insisted \u201cthere Is no reason\nnow to expect any such collapse as\nthat of 1921.\u201d\nPainting, Decorating\nRemodeling\nMetal real \u2022aeelaltet,\